                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                issue
1                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Type II water in 2017: In 2017, the first year nitrogen transformation data were collected, Type II (1 Mohm) water was used to create 2M KCl solutions and conduct extractions. However, this purity is not sufficient and Type I water (18.2 Mohm) has been used for all bouts conducted from 2018 onward. 2017 data was thus collected using a deprecated method and has been flagged accordingly. Moreover, 2 sites extracted in 2017 (JORN AND MOAB) had extremely high ammonium concentrations in both samples and blanks (> 1 mg/L) due to this use of less pure water. These data were deemed unusable, thus values were removed and the records have an additional flag.
2                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Negative inorganic N concentrations: In some nitrogen transformation data, blank-corrected sample concentration values appear significantly negative above background noise, meaning more inorganic N was detected in procedural blanks compared to samples. Extensive troubleshooting has revealed that certain batches of potassium chloride (KCl) used by NEON for extractions have high levels of nitrite, which is chemodenitrified (abiotically converted to nitrogen gas and lost) in the presence of acidic soil, but not in blanks (Homyak et al. 2015). This artifact is what causes the significant negative values and greatly reduces sensitivity of the method for low-concentration sites.
3                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Data products not bundled: Until October 2020, soil physical and chemical properties were published as separate data products.
4                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           No sampling impractical: Prior to the 2020 field season, there was no mechanism to indicate when and why a scheduled sampling event may have been missed.
5  Samples not re-dried: Due to a miscommunication, samples analyzed for carbon (C) and nitrogen (N) concentrations and stable isotopes were not re-dried prior to weighing and analysis at the external lab. While all NEON soil samples are dried at 65C in the domain labs, they are often then stored for weeks to months before being shipped to or analyzed by external labs. During this time they may accumulate moisture, especially in humid areas. Subsequent testing revealed that for organic horizons, %C data are likely underestimated by 1.5-2.5% due to this lack of re-drying prior to analysis. As organic horizon soil samples tend to have high %C (> 20%), this bias may have only minor impacts on many analyses, but is something for end users to keep in mind. For the other parameters (%N, C:N, d15N, d13C) as well as all parameters in mineral horizons, testing suggests there were no detectable differences between re-dried samples and originals.
6                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        Safety measures to protect personnel during the COVID-19 pandemic resulted in reduced or canceled sampling activities for extended periods at NEON sites. Data availability may be reduced during this time.
7                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                Empty data files: A publication error resulted in empty data files for a single site and month of data. These data will be restored in RELEASE-2022.
8                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             sampleID format change: The unique sampling location for each soil core had been included in the primary sample identifier (sampleID) for soil samples and all downstream subsample IDs. Specifically, sampleIDs included the distance east and north of the southwest corner of a plot (in meters). However, including high resolution spatial information in sampleIDs proved problematic when the location was mis-transcribed in the field. Such errors are difficult to detect and very time-consuming to correct.
9                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Toolik Field Station required a quarantine period prior to starting work in the 2020, 2021, and 2022 field seasons to protect all personnel during the COVID-19 pandemic. This complicated NEON field scheduling logistics, which typically involves repeated travel across the state on short time frames. Consequently, NEON reduced staff traveling to Toolik and was thus unable to complete all planned sampling efforts. Missed data collection events are indicated in data records via the samplingImpractical field.
10                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        Severe flooding destroyed several roads into Yellowstone National Park in June 2022, making the YELL and BLDE sites inaccessible to NEON staff. Observational data collection was halted during this time. Canceled data collection events are indicated in data records via the samplingImpractical field.
11                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Alaska soil horizon boundaries: Due to slow rates of organic matter decomposition, organic soils in Alaska sites often appear less decomposed, but are considered soil, compared to organic horizons in CONUS sites. In the early years of sampling, NEON technicians were likely grouping the topâmost fibric material in measurements of litter depth and excluding it from Oâhorizon soil samples.
12                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           pH method change: During periodic soil sampling, pH is measured both in water and calcium chloride. Prior to the 2020 field season, each measurement used separate samples and a 1:2 soil to solution ratio for mineral horizons (organic horizons need higher ratios to saturate the soil). This process was time-consuming and resulted in double the containers needing to be washed.
13                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             Microbial storage changes: In 2021, we began to have issues procuring key supplies for microbial collection and sample preservation. Specifically, some domains could not reliably source dry ice, and all domains could not purchase the 5 mL liquid nitrogen safe cryovials used for microbial genetic archive samples according to the sampling protocol. In order keep collecting, it was necessary to adopt alternate procedures and supplies, but fields did not exist in the data to communicate these changes.
14                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 BARR 2022 missing N-trans: The BARR site was scheduled to conduct soil nitrogen transformations sampling in the summer of 2022. Due to a variety of access issues and bad weather, the NEON team was not able to conduct initial soil sampling until late August. This was too late to install incubation samples for later pickup. As such, there is extractable inorganic N concentration data, but net N transformation rates were not measured (no t-final samples installed).
15                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        Lab summary correction for C-N data: The table `bgc_CNiso_externalSummary` reports the precision and accuracy of carbon and nitrogen concentration and stable isotope measurements of plant and soil samples, based on analysis of secondary reference materials treated as unknowns. The University of Wyoming Stable Isotope Facility had been reporting their summary statistics since 2015 but had mis-interpreted the definitions of some reported uncertainty fields.
16                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          ORNL 2021 missing pH: Following the fall 2021 soil sampling bout at site ORNL, all soil samples were mistakenly discarded before pH measurements could be taken. As such, there are field collected subsamples and moisture data, but no pH measurements.
17                                                                                                                                                                                    KCl analysis protocol issue: As with all external laboratories, the University of Florida Wetland Biogeochemical Lab shared their standard operating procedures (SOPs) for analysis of soil inorganic nitrogen in NEON potassium chloride (KCl) extracts when they started analyzing samples in 2019. However, the documents that have been shared with users for the last several years do not completely reflect procedures used by the lab. There are a few instances of differences in preparation of reagents and/or standard curves between actual lab practices versus what's recorded in publicly available SOP documents. The differences are subtle and should not impact the data quality or reported values, but available documentation should exactly match laboratory practices.
18                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           MLBS 2023 peak green missing N-trans: The MLBS site conducted soil nitrogen transformations sampling during the field season of 2023. Unfortunately, all potassium chloride (KCl) extracts from the peak green bout were destroyed in transit on their way to the analytical lab. Therefore, the data for soil inorganic nitrogen concentrations and net transformation rates will be permanently missing for that bout.

20                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  KCl extracts filter deviation: When extracting soils in potassium chloride (KCl) to determine inorganic nitrogen content, the standard NEON protocol requires use of GF/A filters (Particle Retention = 1.6 Î¼m) to prepare the extracts. However, in Domain 3, GF/C filters (Particle Retention = 1.2 Î¼m) were ordered in March of 2018 and almost certainly used to prepare soil KCl extracts in DSNY in 2018, and quite likely used to prepare KCl extracts from JERC in 2019 and OSBS in 2021.
21                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                Reduced metagenome frequency: For the first several years of NEON sampling, soil microbe metagenome data were produced at all sites annually, during the period of peak greenness. Due to resource constraints, this frequency was not sustainable.
22                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Reduced marker gene frequency: For the first several years of NEON soil sampling, marker gene data were produced for all soil samples at all sites and collection bouts. Due to resource constraints, this frequency was not sustainable.
23                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Sample timing update CLBJ: The seasonal soil sampling schedule for site CLBJ in Domain 11 was designed to capture three distinct periods: the dry to wet transition, the peak vegetation greenness period, and the wet to dry transition. Based on a schedule that used remotely sensed greenness and assumed dry to wet occurred before and wet to dry occurred after this period, the third sampling (labeled sampleTiming = wetDryTransition in sls_soilCoreCollection) generally took place in fall (October/November). Yet over time, experience showed that fall tends to be rainy at the site, and field teams frequently reported they were not capturing the target conditions.
24                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               Biological soil crust: Soils in high-light, low-nutrient environments may support biological soil crusts, a community of bacteria, fungi, moss, and lichens that grow in close association with and stabilize mineral soil. In earlier versions of the NEON soil sampling protocol, it was not recorded when biological soil crusts were present in soil samples, nor were they processed any differently from non-biocrust containing soil samples.

1                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Type I water (18.2 Mohm) has been used for all nitrogen transformation bouts conducted from 2018 onward, and 2017 records have been flagged.
2                                                                                                                                                                                                      Starting with the 2022 sampling season and onward, all batches of reagent-grade potassium chloride purchased for soil extractions are tested for nitrate and nitrite concentrations. Nitrite concentrations of less than 0.02 mg N/L are preferred, although up to 0.05 mg N/L is acceptable when KCl is difficult to source due to supply chain issues. Only batches that meet these purity levels will be used for extractions. This should greatly reduce, although not entirely eliminate, the issue with negative sample values. All samples with concentration values that blank-correct to less than -0.02 mg N/L are flagged with 'blanks exceed sample value' in the nitrateNitriteNQF field, and end users can decide how to treat these data.
3                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        In October 2020, data tables for physical and chemical properties were bundled together in a single data product for improved usability. This applies to all existing and future data.
4                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Starting in the 2020 field season, NEON added the field "samplingImpractical" to the `sls_soilCoreCollection` table of this data product to assist users in understanding when data for this product are temporarily missing versus permanently unavailable. If field collection of soil from a specific subplot within an assigned soil plot was not possible, samplingImpractical is populated with a value other than 'OK' (e.g., 'location flooded' or 'logistical') and only minimal metadata are recorded.
5                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Affected O-horizon data have been flagged with dataQF = dryingProtocolError in the `sls_soilChemistry` table. For sample analysis dates starting in November 2020, all carbon-nitrogen samples (both mineral and organic horizons) are re-dried at 65C prior to analysis to drive out any residual moisture and improve data accuracy for % C. Samples collected in 2020 may have been analyzed before or after the change; check dataQF to determine which individual samples are affected.

11                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 After conferring with the research community, we clarified the instructions for determining the boundary between litter and soil in NEON Alaska sites. From 2018 onward, all nonâgreen, friable fibric material that has roots growing in it is classified as organic soil and sampled as such, rather than being measured as litter. We recommend users keep in mind this method change and use caution when comparing soil data from these five sites collected before and after 2018. Older data have âalaskaDeprecatedMethodâ indicated in the dataQF field in `sls.soilCoreCollection`.
12    In 2020, we adopted the pH method of the USDA Natural Resource Conservation Service, which uses a single container and soil sample to measure pH with both methods. First, water is added to soil and pH is measured at 1:1 soil to solution. Then an equal volume of calcium chloride is added to the same container and pH is measured again at 1:2 soil to solution. These ratios generally apply to mineral soils, more solution is used for organic soils as well as very hygroscopic mineral soils. Soil to solution ratios are recorded in the sls_soilpH table in the 'waterpHRatio' and 'caclpHRatio' fields. Before implementing the change, tests from a small number of sites suggested there would be no impact to the data. However, in reviewing data from all sites after the change was implemented, there may be site-specific effects of the method change on perceived soil pH, especially in water-prepared mineral horizon samples.
13 We issued guidance for storing microbial samples on ultra-cold ice packs when dry ice cannot be sourced. These ice packs are stored overnight in an ultra-low temperature freezer, allowing for temperatures between -60 to -30 C in field coolers for up to eight hours. We added two new fields in the sls.soilCoreCollection table, âgeneticSamplePrepMethodâ and âgeneticArchiveSamplePrepMethodâ to indicate the field preservation method used. Before 2022-02-01, empty values can be interpreted as âdry ice.â Additionally, we allowed storage of frozen archive soil samples in 2 mL liquid nitrogen safe tissue vials when 5 mL cryovials are not available. We added a new field to the sls.soilCoreCollection table, âgeneticArchiveContainerâ to indicate container type and size. Before 2022-08-03, values will be empty. See the Data Product User Guide for general types of frozen archive containers used over time in the NEON project.

19                                                                                                                              The subplot naming convention is updated across all data products with observations and samples that originate from Base plots. The format consists of the identity of the plot point in the southwest corner of the subplot, the scale or size of the subplot, and, for those subplots smaller than 100 m2, the corner of the 100 m2 subplot in which the smaller subplot is located. For example, â21_400â refers to point 21 in the southwest corner and is 400 m2 (20 m x 20 m), and â31_1_1â is a subplot with point 31 in the southwest corner, is 1 m2, and is in corner 1 of the 100 m2 subplot with point 31 in the southwest corner. See the associated Data Notification for further detail: https://www.neonscience.org/impact/observatory-blog/neon-terrestrial-observation-system-tos-base-plot-subplot-renaming.

23                                                                                                                                                                                  Following a deeper analysis of NEON rainfall data, it was determined that the transition season bout names should be swapped. Fall and spring tend to be the wetter periods at the site, while summer (when the site peaks in vegetation greenness) is drier. Thus, the first bout is actually wetDryTransition and the third bout is dryWetTransition. Moreover, the third bout needs to happen earlier to capture the transition from a dry to wet period, thus it was moved up by 1-2 months. When comparing 2025 and later to 2024 and earlier data, the third sampling bout at CLBJ (now sampleTiming = dryWetTransition) will be notably earlier. Moreover, in the 2026 release and onward the transition season bout names are swapped compared to earlier releases.
24                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          NEON worked with biological soil crust experts to develop training materials to help staff recognize biocrust types. When mature biological soil crusts are encountered at NEON soil sampling locations, this is noted in the data using the 'horizonDetails' field in the sls_soilCoreCollection table. Additionally, samples are more thoroughly homogenized prior to microbial subsampling when they have mature biocrusts, either using a 2 mm sieve for sandy soil or by hand for several minutes with clay or loam soil. Groups of sites have been added over time as mature biocrust presence was confirmed.
